      <body>
         <div type="entry">
                <head>Daniel bar Maryam</head>
                <ab type="idnos">
                    <idno type="URI">https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Daniel-bar-Maryam</idno>
                    <idno type="syriaca-bibl">http://syriaca.org/bibl/160</idno>
                    <idno type="entry">151</idno>
                    <milestone unit="pages" n="113"/>
                    <idno type="subject">http://syriaca.org/person/438</idno>
                    <note type="type">person</note>
                    <note type="abstract">Author of an ʿEcclesiastical history’.<note/>
                    </note>
                </ab>
                <ab type="infobox">(7th <abbr>cent.</abbr>) [Ch. of E.]</ab>
                <div type="body">
                    <p>Author of an ‘Ecclesiastical history’. He was a contemporary of <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Ishoyahb-III-of-Adiabene">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/561">Ishoʿyahb III</persName>
                        </ref> (d. 659). His work does not survive, but various
                        authors refer to it, in particular <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Timotheos-I">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/790">Timotheos I</persName>
                        </ref>,
                            <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Gewargis-of-Arbela-Pseudo-">Pseudo-Gewargis of Arbela</ref>, and <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Ishodad-of-Merv">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/555">Ishoʿdad of
                            Merv</persName>
                        </ref> (in his commentary on John). In addition, it is explicitly
                        quoted 5 times in the Arabic Chronicle of <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Siirt">
                            <placeName ref="http://syriaca.org/place/188">Siirt</placeName>
                        </ref>, which has led
                        scholars to suggest that it was used as a direct source by the <choice>
                     <sic>Chronicler</sic>
                     <corr>chronicler</corr>
                  </choice> (along with two other 7th-cent. historians whose works have not been
                        preserved, Eliya of Merv and Bar Sahde). Daniel’s Ecclesiastical History is
                        mentioned by <ref rend="bold" target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Abdisho-bar-Brikha">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/310">ʿAbdishoʿ bar
                            Brikha</persName>
                        </ref>, along with a work dealing with chronology (which is not
                        otherwise known). Perhaps Daniel bar Maryam is the same person as <ref rend="bold"
                       target="https://gedsh.bethmardutho.org/Daniel-bar-Tubanitha">
                            <persName ref="http://syriaca.org/person/439">Daniel bar Ṭubanitha</persName>
                        </ref>.</p>
                </div>
                <div type="bibl">
                    <head>Sources</head>
